### Step[5]
Analysis: We followed the prescribed workflow: preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root-cause localization. Preprocessing: global thresholds (P95/P90/P05) were computed per component-KPI using the full metric series. Data were then filtered to the incident window (2024-01-20 04:17:04 → 2024-01-20 04:47:04 UTC). Metric analysis: many component-KPI series exceeded their global P95 in-window. Notable findings: (1) carts had the largest aggregated anomaly count (38) across multiple KPIs and contained a very large disk I/O spike (carts.diskio max ≈ 97583.76 while its global P95 was 0), with the earliest carts.diskio anomaly at 2024-01-20 04:20:00 UTC. (2) Several services (catalogue, user, payment) showed socket KPI anomalies at P95 beginning at 2024-01-20 04:20:00 UTC, indicating widespread socket/connection-related activity. (3) Other services (orders) also showed diskio anomalies. Trace data were absent (trace.csv empty) so we could not use traces for call-chain localization. Log analysis: no error_count increases or error_messages were present in the incident window; front-end traffic (log.row_count) peaked repeatedly during the window (high request load), but downstream services did not log elevated error counts.

Interpretation: the metrics present two correlated signals starting at ~04:20 UTC — widespread socket/connection anomalies across multiple services and pronounced disk I/O spikes (most severe on carts). The carts service is the predominant metric outlier by both anomaly count and by extreme deviation (diskio jumped from normally 0 to ~9.8e4). Given the absence of trace data, and that logs show heavy front-end traffic but no logged errors, the most plausible root cause is a resource saturation on the carts service (disk I/O) that coincides with high request load and also associates with abnormal socket metrics across services (either as a secondary symptom or as increased connection/queueing activity). The earliest detected fault point is carts.diskio at 2024-01-20 04:20:00 UTC.
Instruction: Diagnosis summary (final answer):
- Root-cause component: carts
- Failure reason: high disk I/O usage (diskio saturation)
- First occurrence: 2024-01-20 04:20:00 UTC (first carts.diskio anomaly in the incident window)
- Evidence: carts had the highest aggregate anomaly count (38) and an extreme diskio spike (max ≈ 97583.8 vs global P95 = 0). Multiple services showed socket anomalies beginning at the same time, and front-end traffic peaked during the window, but logs show no error_count increases; traces are unavailable. The magnitude and concentration of carts disk I/O anomalies make carts.diskio the most likely root cause rather than network-only causes. 
- Recommended next steps: investigate carts I/O subsystem (disk, database access pattern, blocking I/O, queueing), check carts instance host disk metrics and underlying storage, and correlate with front-end traffic surge to determine whether traffic rate triggered the I/O saturation.
